6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"MEXC uses 8-hour funding cycles typical of CEXs with rate calculations based on premium and interest components. Drift employs 1-hour funding intervals allowing for more frequent rate adjustments and better tracking of spot-perp basis. MEXC's rates can be more volatile due to longer intervals and potential manipulation in thin markets. Drift's vAMM model creates more predictable funding patterns but depends heavily on oracle accuracy. Both exchanges use mark price vs index price differentials but Drift's frequent updates reduce basis risk."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange has better funding rate opportunities?","answer":"MEXC's 8-hour cycles can create larger rate discrepancies but with higher execution risk. Drift's 1-hour intervals offer more frequent arbitrage opportunities with better predictability but smaller rate differentials."},{"question":"How do the fee structures impact arbitrage profitability?","answer":"MEXC's zero maker fees significantly reduce costs for market makers, while Drift's 0.02% maker fee is offset by potential MEV protection and JIT liquidity benefits. Trading volume and frequency determine which structure is more profitable."},{"question":"What are the main technical risks for each platform?","answer":"MEXC faces counterparty risk and potential regulatory issues as a centralized exchange. Drift depends on Solana network stability and smart contract security, with additional complexity from its hybrid vAMM/DLOB model."},{"question":"Which platform offers better liquidity for large positions?","answer":"MEXC generally provides deeper liquidity for major pairs but with quality concerns. Drift's JIT auctions can provide competitive execution for larger orders despite lower base liquidity, particularly during volatile periods."}]}]
